{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_kaffirlily_ver01/data/sn82007637/00340580382/1945090701/1008.xml":{"full_text":"a\nScale Workers To\nPick Union Today\nUAW Favored To J! in In\nThird Plant Election\nTime\nLocal 12, UAW-CIO is favored to win today\u2019s election,\nthe third in slightly more than three years at the Toledo\nScale Co. plant to determine a bargaining agent for com\npany employees.\nContinued on Page 2\nCIO Official Joins\nPrincipals in the ballot contest will be the UAW-CIO\nof Local 12 and the Scale\nfor\nPlain Talk\nTom Burke\nVice-President\nLocal 12,\nUAW-CIO\nrU\nLast week, Leroy Hartman\nand I, acting on the request of\nRegional Director Richard\nGosser, hitched a trailer be\nhind our car nad took the po\nlio pock machine invented by\nmembers of the Spicer Polio\nCommittee over to Rockford,\nIll., where a serious infantile\nparalysis epidemic has existed\nfor some time.\nNurses, doctors and J. D.\n\u2018Tennock, head of the National\nInfantile Paralysis Foundation,,.\nat Rockford, were really hap-\nSf py to see us. The overworked\nnurses were especially pleased\nwith the Spicer machine, for\nit made it possible for them to\ntreat dozens of additional pa\ntients and really helped out\nmore than a little.\nUAW REQUEST\nOur mission to Rockford\ncame as the result of a re\nquest for aid by UAW-CIO\nRegional Director Joe Mattson\nwho contacted vice-president\nWalter,Reuther in Detroit and\nasked him to see what he\ncould do to get the machine\nfor Rockford. Walter Reuther\nin turn called Director Gosser\nwho sent us on our way to\nof Staff Here\nArt' Kochendorfer, President\nof the northern Ohio district\ncouncil of the American News\npaper Guild, which is active in\norganizing newspaper workers\nin northern Ohio for the CIO,\ntook up new Aities with the\nToledo Chambdl 4*xf Commerce\nSeptember 5.\nIn addition to his other work,\nMr. Kochendorfer will edit\n\u201cToledo Business,\u201d official\nChamber publication.\nMr. Kochendorfer has been\nemployed by the Toledo Times\nfor the past three years and\ncovered the labor boat for that\n9\u2018 paper. He is a former chair\nman of the Times Unit of the\nToledo Newspaper Guild. He\nhas been editing \u201cToledo Busi\nness\u201d for some time past.\nEmployment Offices\nCutting ray Scales\nWorkers of Ohio, Inc., a so\ncalled \u201cindependent\u201d union\nwhich has had the plant bargain\ning rights lor the past three\nyears.\nEver since the first plant elec\ntion in December of 1942 when\nthe \u201cindependent\u201d union won\nover the UAW-CIO by a major\nity of 96 votes, the trend has\ngradually swung to the Auto\nWorkers. Last year\u2019s election\nsaw the Scale Workers of Ohio\ncut to a slim 26-vote majority.\nDissatisfaction on Increase\nSince the 1944 election, the\nswing to the UAW-CIO has con\ntinued due to the disatisfaction\nof a growing number of Scale\nCo. workers. This is due in large\nmeasure to the instability of the\ntop union leadership, according\nto members of the \u201cindepen\ndent\u201d union who point out that\neach year for the past three years\nthere has been a complete change\nof top officers.\nHow true the contention of\nmany Scale Workers is was\nshown recently when employes\nof the purchasing department,\nmembers of the \u201cindependent\u201d\norganization quit the union in\ndisgust and termed it \u201cchaotic.\u201d\n^Adding strength, to the trend\naway from the Scale Workers of\nOhio is the increasing number of\n\u201cindependent\u201d shop organiza\ntions turning to bona fide unions\neither by affiliation or outright\nrepudiation of what union mem\nbers refer to as \u201ccompany dom\ninated unions.\u201d This has become\nparticularly marked in recent\nmonths and is believed to be due\nto frequent cases where the com\npany management influences or\nactually dictates the policies of\nthe \u201cindependent\u201d organizations.\nSee Possible Victory\nUAW-CIO adherents in the\nScale Co. plant believe that many\nof the workers there prefer a\nbona fide union particularly now\nthat the War Labor Board is in\nprocess of liquidation. They\npoint out that experienced men\nare required to conduct negotia\ntions and collective bargaining\nand then compare their inexperi\nenced officials with those of the\nAuto Workers who have secured\nsome of the finest union con\ntracts existing in the United\nStates.\nVictory for the UAW is be\nlieved to be quite possible in to\nday\u2019s election due to the many\nfactors which have influenced\nScale employes against their\nunion because of its consistent\nfailure to make worthwhile gains\nin wages or other benefits for\nthe worker.\nHours for voting will be from\n3 to 6 p. m. in a booth in the\ncompany\u2019s parking lot. Results\nof the election will be deter\nmined by NLRB officials who\nwill tabulate and announce the\noutcome of the balloting. Certi\nfication of the winning union as\nplant bargaining agent will be\nmade soon after the election.\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 4 (LPA)\u2014As long lines of unem\nployed workers form to apply for justly earned unemploy\nment benefits during the reconversion period, they are\nlearning a few of the restrictions that are operating to make\nthe social security system and the U. S. Employment Serv\nice agencies for lowering U.\nS. wage levels.\nControversy among labor,\nmanagement and state officials\nhas broken out in Michigan, Mis\nsouri, Connecticut, New York,\nand the District of Columbia, to\nmention only a few places.\nMain cause of the controversy\nis the question of whether a\nworker who refuses work at\nwages considerably lower than\nhis previous employment is en\ntitled to unemployment compen\nsation,\nClash Th Connecticut\nIn Connecticut, Edward Lave\nry, president of the Industrial\nUnion Council, has taken the po\u00ad\nsition that no limitations should\nbe placed on the administration\nof the fund and that if an un\nemployed worker applies for\nbenefits he is entitled to them.\nHe has clashed with the Con\nnecticut Manufacturer Ass\u2019n,\nwhich contends that this would\ncreate an artificial labor short\nage.\nIn New York State, both CIO\nand AFL have repeatedly pro\ntested similar rulings by the Di\nrector of the State Division of\nUnemployment Insurance.\nThe Central Labor Union of\nSt. Louis has protested the ac\ntions of the State Unemployment\nContinued on Page 3\nSigns advising everyone to\n\u201cJoin PAC 80,000,000 Jobs\nNeeded for War\u2014Necessary for\nPeace\u201d and similar slogans were\nscattered liberally throughout\nthe entire line of\nmarch.\nFloats Make Hit\nFloats entered by the various\nLocals and Units attracted con\nsiderable attention and \u2019more\nthan a little applause from the\nthousands of spectators who\ncrowded the entire 30-block line\nof march. Scoring the biggest\nhit and winning first prize was\nthe float entered by the Textile\nworkers of Local 224 depicting\nthe flag raising on Iwo Jima.\nOne word, \u201cRemember,\u201d was\nfastened to the side of the float.\nElectric Auto-Lite of Local 12,\nUAW-CIO, won second prize\nwith its float entitled \u201cThe Past\nand the Future,\u201d with a soldier\nin a foxhole on one side and\nworkers at machines oa the\nother.\nTied for third place were\nChampion Unit and Willys-Over\nland Unit, both of Local 12. The\nformer carried pretty girls in\nshorts and sweaters, the latter\nentitled \u201cThe Horn of Plenty\u201d\nwith jobs for everybody.\nToledo Steel Tube Unit, Local\n12, won honorable mention for\nits float bearing a replica of the\nStatue of Liberty.\nLocal 12 Is Largest\nAs usual, Local 12 was the\nlargest Unit in line. Several\nthousand members of the Unit\nbore pennants carrying the in\nscription, \u201cLocal 12, Ohio\u2019s Larg\nest and Friendliest Union.\u201d\nContinued on Page 2\nSkilled Worfee rs\nMembers of the Greater\nToledo Tool, Die and Main\ntenance Workers Council\nwill hold their regular\nmeeting Sept. 10 at 8 p. m.\nat Local 12 headquarters,\n425 Winthrop St.\nUnemployed members of\nthe Council are urged to\ncome to the Sept. 10 meet\ning to register for employ\nment.\nNew office hours for the\nCouncil are from 8 to 9:30\np. m. Mondays and Fridays,\nfourth floor, 424 Winthrop\nSt.\nK|\nI\nK\n7\"''\u2122\nThousands of CIO members marching in\nthe 1945 Labor Day parade made an impres\nsive showing with their signs illustrating la\nbor\u2019s postwar demands for increased unem\nployment benefits, full employment and im\u00ad\nThousands Parade In\nLabor Day Celebration\nTextile Workers Win Prize\nDepicting Iwo Jima Scene\n^Despite '40,000 unemployed since V-J Day, 10,000 C1C\nmembers representing all the International Unions in this\ncity turned out last Monday to march in the greatest Labor\nDay in five years.\nVictory, reconversion, full employment and PAC were\nthe principal themes of the\nparade with practically every\nmarcher carrying banners\nand signs outlining the CIO pro\ngram for postwar America.\nANG Guild\nVol. 3, No. 40 48,000 Circulation TOLEDO, OHIO, FRIDAY, SEPT. 7, 1945 Price 5e\nCongress Assembles For Important Session\n(N w_____ _______ I ______\u25a0_ _______\nLegislature Votes Increased Unemployment Benefits\nCIO Shows Labor Day Spirit\nw\nO'Malley Sladers\nNEW YORK (LPA) Sept. 4\u2014\nMr. O\u2019Malley, almost infallible\ngodfather of the comic strip\ncharacter Barnaby, slipped last\nweek. It seems that, in the strip,\nhe\u2019s been doing some calumn\nwriting on the side, and remem\nbered that he\u2019d let his Guild\nmembership lapse. And, mused\nO\u2019Malley, the Guild has a closed\nshop on the paper.\nThat, pointed out hundreds of\nindignant members of the Amer\nican Newspaper Guild-CIO, is a\nslander. The ANG has no closed\nshop contracts it prefers the\nunion shop agreement with\nmanagement.\nTo straighten things out, and\nsalve O\u2019Malley\u2019s wounded feel\nings, the New York Guild has\noffered to give O\u2019Malley a new\nGuild card if he ever again be\ncomes a newspaperman.\nPayoff is that the comic edi\ntor of PM, the paper with which\nthe strip originates, is an execu\ntive of the New York Guild!\n\u2018A\naA.\u25a0v.\nKO\"\nproved social security legislation, Despite\nWidespread unemployment, 10,000 loyal mem\nbers of CIO proudly marched to commemorate\nfinal military, victory and their part in making\nIt possible.\nThemas, Wife\nReconciled\nDETROIT, Sept. 1 (Special)\u2014\nR. j) Thomas, president of the\nUAW- CIO and his wife have\nbeen reconciled it was reported\n.here this week by the current is\nsue of \u201cThe Wage Earner\u201d offi\ncial ACTU organ published in\nthis city. The divorce suit filed\nby the president of the Auto\nWorkers is expected to be with\ndrawn.\nThe Wage Earner reported\nthat there was no formal an\nnouncement from either Thomas\nor his wife, but said they -had\nappeared together recently at so\ncial gatherings at the homes of\nfriends.\nBoth Mr. and Mrs. Thomas are\nmembers of Chrysler Local 7,\nUAW-CIO. Thomas appeared be\nfore a recent meeting of the Lo\ncal and inferred that he and\nMrs. Thomas had made up their\ndifferences. He told the meeting\nthat he believed his domestic\ndifficulties were due in great\nmeasure to the fact that he has\nbeen away from home on union\nbusiness so frequently.\nTune In WTOL Thursday At 7:30 p. m.\nCIO Remembers FDR\nWASHINGTON (LPA) A\nCIO sponsored \u201cliving memo\nrial\u201d to Franklin Delano Roose\nvelt\u2014a children\u2019s wing in the\nGeorgetown Hospital now .un\nder construction here\u2014was an\nnounced last week. An appro\npriation of $55,000 has been au\nthorized by the CIO executive\nboard, and will be used to pre\npare and equip the whole fifth\nfloor section of several wards\nfor children.\nUSES Ires Workers\nWith Runaround\nWage Cutting Aided By\nEmployment Agency\nEvidence continues to pile up that the local United\nStates Employment service has become a competent aid to\nToledo employers in the wage cutting program which was\ninaugurated with the end of the war and its resultant un\nemployment.\nResentment on the part of\nthe workers is growing over\nthe methods used by em\nployes of the USES office in\nhanding out jobs, particularly\nskilled jobs, according to infor\nmation furnished this newspa\nper by many who have applied\nfor such jobs and been told there\nwere none.\nBodette Outlines Jobs\nEdward J. Bodette, in charge\nof the Toledo, USES office when\ninterviewed by the TOLEDO\nUNION JOURNAL last week\nstated that out of more than\n1800 jobs open for men on\nAugust 31, approximately 400\nwere skilled trades openings.\nHe said that of the 733 jobs\navailable for women that the\nlargest number were for domes\ntic and similar low wage help\nOf the jobs open for men, the\nmajority were what he termed\n\u201cmine run\u201d paying from 50 to\n75 cents per hour as laborers\nThese are the jobs which are\nbeing offered to the male work\ners who apply for work with the\nlargest share paying an hourly\nrate of 50 cents.\nMr. Bodette stated that \u201cin\nsofar as possible, we send peo\nple out on jobs for which they\nare fitted.\u201d Evidence to the\ncontrary has been accumulating\nthat many skilled people have\nContinued on Page 2\nLegion Insults\nLabor Unions\nCHICAGO (LPA) Sept. 4\nThe American Legion is once\nmore under attack by its labor\nmembers because in recent\nmonths it has turned down two\napplications one by an AFL\nand one by a CIO body for\nchartering new posts.\nOnly reason given by the Le\ngion is that no new posts are\nbeing chartered. This, accord\ning to Judge Advocate Maurice\nA. Frank of the National Con\nference of Union Labor Legion\nnaires, is a \u201cweak excuse\u201d and\n\u201criduculous.\u201d\nTurned down were applica\ntions from the Buffalo Federa\ntion of Labor for a Union Labor\nPost, and the Kansas City, Mo.,\nIndustrial Union Council for a\nJohn W. Yates Post.\nAt the same time, Frank\npoints out, the Legion boasts\nthat a Franklin D. Roosevelt\nPost has been set up in the\nliquor industry in New York.\nNational Commander Edward\nN. Scheiberling has been asked\nto \u201ctake immediate steps to\nright these wrongs.\u201d Appeals\nhave also been directed to the\nLegion\u2019s National Labor Rela\ntions Committee, with a request\nthat the refusal of charters be\nreviewed by them, and recom\nmendations made to the next\nLegion convention now sched\nuled la Chicago for this fall.\nLazette Asks CIO\nWar Chest Aid\nThis Is considered to be our\nbanner year in the history of or\nganized labor. We can feel\nmighty proud of our record in\nof_ materials\nn e e s sary to\nbring about the\ncomplete vic\ntory w\u2019hich we\nare enjoying\ntoday. We can\nalso feel equal\nly as proud of\nour record in\nour giving to\nthe Greater To\nledo Commun\nity War Chest,\nwhich greatly aided those who\nwere in distress.\nthe production\nwhich wexe\nRichard Lazette\nEven though the war is over\ninsofar as actual combat is con\ncerned, our war against need and\nwant is just as great, and, per\nhaps, will be even larger due to\nunemployment and other situa\ntions which now confront us.\nThe Toledo CIO Council rep\nresenting all CIO in Toledo, has\nwholeheartedly endorsed the\ncoming Chest campaign as a must\non our program. We have the\nhonor of being the largest indi\nvidual giver to the Chest, as an\norganization, in the city of To\nledo.\nNow that the servicemen have\nmore leisure, the USO is being\nexpanded and it will need more\nfunds to meet the costs of a\ngreatly enlarged program until\nall those in the armed forces re\nturn home. The local Chest agen\ncies\u2019 needs will also be greatly\nexpanded until after the recon\nversion period. The amount of\nmoney needed for local agencies\nwill be the same as last year.\nThis will be the last campaign\nfor war-related agencies.\nBe generous in victory. Help\ncarry the unemployed brother\nand sister who cannot give this\nyear.\n\u2014Richard Lazette\nTune In WTOL Thursday At 7:30 p. m.\nIndiana Signs\nL-M Charter\nSOUTH BEND, Ind. (LPA)\u2014\nRepresentatives of AFL, CIO.\nand management with the\nblessing of the state govern\nment, met here last week and\nsigned an Indiana State Labor\nManagement Charter, first oi\nits kind in the state, and one of\nthe first in the country. Each\ngroup is pledged to a \u201cgive and\ntake\u201d conference-table settle\nment of future labor problems.\nDrivers\u2019 Licenses\nTom Burke, Local 12,\nvice-president has been\nnamed deputy registrar for\ndrivers licenses which will\nbe placed on sale Sept. 10\nthrough the Local 12 Serv\nice Bureau, Room 203, 42$\nWinthrop St. Mr. Burke re-\nminds veterans that they\nmust present an honorable\ndischarge or a certified\ncopy in order to obtain\ntheir licenses.\nUnions Join\nForces For\nModification\nCOLUMBUS. Sept. 5 (Spe\ncial)\u2014Confining itself to vot\ning through emergency and\nretroactive clauses for the\nnew unemployment compen\nsation act originally scheduled to\ngo into effect Oct. 12. the Ohio\nState Senate late today turned\ndown \u00bbvery attempt from the\nDemocratic side to liberalize the\nbill by amendments.\nMembers of the House with a\nRepublican majority were ex\npected to line up in a night ses\nsion in the same way and pass\nthe emergency and retroactive\nclause which would make the un\nemploy nent compensation bill\nproviding $21 for 22 weeks ef\nfective as of Aug. 15 and mean\nmillions of dollars in extra bene\nfits to those who are unemployed\nwho have already registered with\nthe United States Employment\nService.\nRefuse Liberal Amendments\nHaving given wiln one hand,\nthe Republican legislators re\nfused to go farther in accepting\nliberalizing amendments which\nwould have eased some of the in\nterpretations placed upon the\nbill. One amendment offered by\nSenator Walsh (D.) of Dayton,\nwould have written a \u201csuitable\nwork\u201d definition into the law. At\nthe present time, one third of all\napplicants for unemployment\nbenefits are denied because they\nrefuse to accept jobs unsuited to\ntheir skills, health, etc.\nLt. Governor Nye again re\nvealed himself as too studious\nin his handling of the gavel when\nhe objected to applause from\nhundreds of workers who had\ncome from all sections of the\nstate. He was* challenged from\nthe floor lor his quick effort* to\ni Continued on Page 2\nBowling Green\nPlant Picks\nAuto Workers\nBOWLING GREEN. Sept. 1\n(Special* Employees of the\nDaybrooke Hydraulic Hoist Co.\nof this city voted in favor of the\nUnited Auto Workers-CIO in an\nNLRB conducted election on\nAugust 1. Defeated was the AFL\nwhich has held the plant bar\ngaining rights for the past two\nyears.\nResults of the balloting gave\nCIO-98 votes. AFL-33.\nOrville Beemer, International\nUAW-CIO representative from\nthe office of Regional Director\nRichard Gosser of Toledo stated\nthat the contract which was ap\nproved by the membership\nwould be submitted to the com\npany management on Sept. 4.\nActual organizational work in\nthe plant by the UAW was\nslightly in excess of 30 days ac\ncording to Mr. Beemer.\nTune In WTOL Thursday At 7:3* p. m.\nWomen Want Work\nWASHINGTON (LPA)\nWomen in the Baltimore area\nwant to\u2014and need to\u2014keep on\nworking, a Women\u2019s Bureau of\nthe Department of Labor sur\nvey reported last week. Two\nthirds of them are single or\nwidows, and one of every seven\nis the sole wage-earner in the\nfamily. Eighty per cent want\npostwar jobs, preferably in fac\ntories, and 95 per cent want to\nstay in the same area. Take\nhome pay averaged $34 in the\nwar plants as against $21 in the\nstores and laundries, since these\nare not covered by the Federal\nFair Labor Standards Act.\nThe Voire of the\n(IO\nin\nherthicestern Ohio\nLabor Forces\nUnite On Full\nEmployment\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 5\n(Special)\u2014Members of Con\ngress assembled here today\nto face one of the most im\nportant sessions in the his\ntory of the country. Reconver\nsion, unemployment compensa\ntion, full employment and other\nimportant legislation awaiting\nhearings or up for debate and\nvote will provide a full docket\nfor the nations\u2019 law givers in the\ncoming weeks.\nLooming large on the horizon\nis the unemployment compensa\nsation bill which President Trii\nman will probably name as\n\u201cmust\u201d legislation, as well as\nthe full employment bill which\nhas been given the united back\ning of all labor.\nBusiness Opposes Bill\nBusiness attempts to discredit\nand further emasculate the Mur\nray Full Employment Bill were\ncontested by labor spokesmen,\nrepresentatives of Federal agen\ncies and municipal officials in\nthe final week of hearings be\nfore the sub-committee of the\nSenate Banking and Currency\nCommittee chaired by Sen.\nRobert W\u2019agner (D N. Y.)\nIndustry attitudes ranged from\noutright opposition to the bill,\nto \u201cendorsement\u201d of the princi\nples of the bill. However, such\nsupport was usually accompa\nnied by amendments aimed at\nfurther weakening of the bill.\nNat\u2019l Ass\u2019n of Manufacturer\u2019s\nPresident Ira Mosher led off the\nweeks\u2019 testimony for business in\na statement opposing the meas\nure, but contending that bust\nness was wholeheartedly tor\n1 full employment.\nSecretary Wallace, appearing\nin support of the bill, contend\nContinued on Page 2\n\nTo Liquidate\nWMC Offices\nCOLUMBUS, Ohio, Aug. 31\u2014\nLiquidation in the next 30 days\nof five of the 11 area offices of\nthe War Manpower Commission\nin Ohio and a consequent state\nwide reduction of WMC person\nnel from the present staff of 94\nto 51. was announced here to\nday by John L. Ccaig, state\nWMC director.\nYoungstown, Canton, Bridge\nport, Dayton. Lancaster-Ports\nmouth and Lima-Troy-Sidney\nare the areas designated by\nCraig to discontinue no later\nthan October 1. Personnel in\nthese offices affected by Craig\u2019*\nmemorandum total 23.\nArea offices which will con\nt\u2019nue to function are Cleveland,\nToledo, Akron, Columbus and\nCincinnati, where employment\nproblems closely related to re\nconversion to civilian economy\nremain so complex that it will\nbe necessary for WMC to con\ntinue its labor market evalua\ntions and job development pro\ngram.\nBed News Travels Fast\nNEWARK, N. J. (LPA)\u2014The\nWestern Union offices here\nwere swamped last week with\njob layoff and contract cancel\nlation messages to the point\nwhere the supervisor said he\ncould use \u201ceverything on\nwheels\u201d to get the telegrams\ndelivered. Three hundred pri\nvate automobiles and trucks\nwere already in use, carrying\nthe \u201cyou're out of a job\" mes\nsages. _________ _____\nCheck Shows Two\nMillion Unemployed\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 4 (LPA)\u2014There are at least\n2,000,000 workers who have been laid off so far in war con\ntract cutbacks. This is the conclusion of the statisticians at\nthe War Manpower Commission, at the end of the first week\nunder a new reporting system designed to get some sort of\naccurate picture of unem\nployment, and jobs available,\nin the nation as a whol\u00ae.\nThere were 1.500,000 workers\nunemployed before the Japanese\nsurrender, according to WMC,\nand the 2,000,000 figure does not\ninclude workers in service in\ndustries who lost their jobs\nwhen war work closed down\nplants, nor men discharged from\nthe armed forces. It is based on\ntelegraphic reports from 73\nareas.\nIn a longer-range prediction,\nWMC last week listed the areas\nwhere from 20 to 25% of the\nworkers w\u2019ill be job hunting by\nmid October. The nine areas\nthat will be \u201cdistressed\u201d accord\ning to WMC are: Portland, Me.\nBuffalo-Niagara Falls. N. Y. De\ntroit and Flint. Mich. Talla\ndega, Ala. Panama City, Fla.\nWichita, Kan. Los Angeles,\nCalif., and Portland, Ore.","height":"26949","width":"20382"}}
